DIYs or going natural certainly is a good idea but I think it should be well researched before it is promoted. What I found most alarming in the video is using cat litter as a mask. Clay cat litter is dusty and can cause respiratory issues. It's bad enough to begin with but it gets worse when it gets wet (clumping or not) they tend to stick together and so if you inhale some of that stuff it can cause lung inflammation. Also, just because it's marked organic doesn't mean it's actually organic. In certain places in North America, the actual food company does the inspection since it costs less. It's hard to believe and it's quite unfortunate but food isn't 100% regulated by the State. As for serums and oils, I think it's actually better to just consume the vitamin. As you can see in this video and just look at the labels, these serums and oils only have a certain amount of the vitamin in it. Why not just cut a vitamin E pill and apply the serum on your face? I was fooled by this too. I purchased the Vitamin E serum in oil from The Body Shop and it made no difference in my skin. They put vitamins or serums in carriers (TBS put in an oil) so it gets diluted and it allows them to make the product more afforadable. Yes, it's affordable but you're not really getting the most out of it. These type of videos are definitely a great idea. And who doesn't want to save themselves some money? But is it really worth it? Is it worth risking your health?

Oil is the devil for acne-prone and oily skin, because it is occlusive. All kind of skins can use it to remove makeup (I do too and i'm acne-prone), but unless you have very dry and unlikely to get impure skin, you absolutely have to wash your face with a cleanser after using oil.
Do not listen to those telling you that cleansing with oils works better for acne-prone skin, it's false. They tell you that since "like dissolves like", oil takes away your skin oils: it's false, plant oils aren’t actually that similar to the oil produced by your skin (which actually isn’t an oil at all, rather it is a mix of waxes and other substances).
Remove makeup with oil if you like that, but wash your face with a gentle cleanser afterwards, unless you do want to make your skin worse than it is...

I would not recommend putting Apple Cider Vinegar (organic unfiltered or otherwise) directly onto the skin. It is too acidic and will disrupt the pH balance of the skin, especially in youths with acne. The switch-and-mix method is still damaging. The best option is to dissolve 1 part ACV with 2 parts water, before applying as toner. That said, ACV is still best taken as a drink actually, because the beneficial properties of ACV comes out in digestion, as it changes from Acidic to Alkaline from within the body.

Honestly I think all this is a little over kill, I keep my routine pretty simple, for AM cleansing I wash my face with plain old warm tap water or warm tap water with a little Aloe Vera gel mixed in " Now brand" , next I lightly soak a disposable cotton pad with rose water" Heritage store brand" and gently rub it onto my whole face. PM right before bed I wash with warm water and aloe vera mixed with a pinch of rice flour for gentle exfoliation, followed with rose water toning, and last I apply a thin layer of cold pressed organic hemp seed oil. This cost me under $30. My point of this post is not that my routine or products will work for everyone but that you don't have to run out and buy tons of expensive "high end" products to put on your face to find something that works for you.
